{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_0","type":"agent_message","text":"final_filename: p3.cir\n\nObjective: Create an NMOS common-drain amplifier (source follower) using node Vin as the gate input and node Vout as the source output. The circuit should operate from VDD = 5 V and include a resistive load from Vout to ground. Verify DC operating point and small-signal AC follower behavior.\n\nTopology: Use one NMOS transistor with drain connected to VDD, gate connected to Vin, source connected to Vout, and bulk tied to source at Vout. Place a load resistor R from Vout to ground. Drive Vin with an explicit independent voltage source that provides a DC gate bias high enough for conduction and saturation, plus a small-signal AC input.\n\nRequired devices:\n- VDD independent DC supply from node VDD to 0, value 5 V.\n- Vin independent voltage source from node Vin to 0, with DC bias at least 1.2 V. Prefer DC 2.5 V and AC 1 V for gain measurement.\n- M1 NMOS with drain VDD, gate Vin, source Vout, bulk Vout.\n- Rload from Vout to 0, choose a value in the allowed 10k-100k range, nominally 10k or 47k.\n- NMOS model: Vth=0.7V, kp=100u, W=50u, L=1u.\n\nBiasing assumptions: With Vin biased around 2.5 V and Rload to ground, Vout should settle below Vin by approximately Vgs, forming a valid source follower operating point. Bulk must be tied to source to avoid body effect. The drain at VDD should keep the NMOS in saturation when VDS >= VGS - Vth.\n\nAnalyses:\n- Include `.op` to verify DC operating point, especially V(Vin), V(Vout), NMOS region, and drain current.\n- Include `.ac dec 20 1 1e9` to verify small-signal gain from Vin to Vout. Vin source must include `AC 1`.\n\nOutput constraints: The final netlist must be saved as `p3.cir`. The exact node names `Vin` and `Vout` must appear in the netlist. Vin must be electrically driven by an explicit independent source. Vout must be the NMOS source node and the top of the resistive load. No subcircuits or floating input/output nodes."}}
